         <abstract>
            <p>A large and rapidly growing group of federally assisted lending programs--comprising $20 billions worth of borrowing in fiscal 1971--is not included in the budget. On one hand, they benefit some borrowers at the expense of others, since they pre-empt private funds otherwise allocated by market forces; on the other, they avoid having to compete for public funds with programs included in the budget. Much of this lending is unnecessarily expensive to the U. S. taxpayer since it is financed at rates above those enjoyed by the Treasury. Still another problem with this lending is the fact that, falling outside the budget, it is not coordinated with the government's economic stabilization policies.</p>
          </abstract>
